Author::::spidermoney
DateTime::::2016-03-03T23:51:20Z
Sorry, but I don't think Crowe was anything like David Gower. The young Martin Crowe was very straight, very solid, playing long in the V before expanding an innings. He was rigorous in his technique, though as he aged he tended to hit the ball squarer than straighter. Gower was much more of an "eye" player, wafting at the ball, bat far from his body. But how he connected! The young Gower was glorious and you thought, how are we ever going to stop this man? As he aged he seemed to miss more than he connected, and batting became less a certainty than an adventure, ultimately less an adventure than a misadventure.



